defs.docs:
The goal of this crate is to provide Rust bindings to the Web APIs and to allow
 a high degree of interoperability between Rust and JavaScript.

defs.name: from_reference_unchecked

Converts a given reference into a concrete reference-like wrapper.

defs.name: DiscardOnDrop
defs.docs:
If you have a value which implements [`Discard`](https://docs.rs/discard/%5E1.0.3/discard/trait.Discard.html), you can use
 [`DiscardOnDrop::new(value)`](struct.DiscardOnDrop.html#method.new) which will wrap the value.
 When the wrapper is dropped it will automatically call [`value.discard()`](https://docs.rs/discard/%5E1.0.3/discard/trait.Discard.html#tymethod.discard).

attributes.value:
must_use =
  "

     The DiscardOnDrop is unused, which causes it to be immediately discarded.
     You probably don't want that to happen.

     How to fix this:

       * Store the DiscardOnDrop in a variable or data structure.

       * Or use the leak() method which will cause it to not be
         discarded (this will usually leak memory!)

     See the documentation for more details.
"

CORS requests for this element will have the credentials flag set;
 this means the request will provide credentials.

defs.name: Date
defs.docs:
[(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date)
 https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-date-constructor

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates a JavaScript Date instance that represents a single moment in time.
 Date objects are based on a time value that is the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 UTC.

defs.name: from_datetime
defs.value: fn (year: i32, month: i32, day: i32, hours: i32, minutes: i32, seconds: i32, milliseconds: i32) -> Self
defs.docs:
Creates a JavaScript Date instance that represents a single moment in time.
 Date objects are based on a time value that is the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 UTC.
 
 year is an integer value representing the year. Values from 0 to 99 map to the years 1900 to 1999.
 month is an integer value representing the month, beginning with 0 for January to 11 for December
 day is an integer value representing the day of the month (normally from 1 to 31)
 hours an integer value representing the minute segment of a time
 seconds an integer value representing the second segment of a time
 milliseconds an integer value representing the millisecond segment of a time

defs.name: from_iso8601
defs.docs:
Creates a JavaScript Date instance that represents a single moment in time.
 Date objects are based on a time value that is the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 UTC.
 
 String value representing a date. The string should be in a format recognized by
 the Date.parse() method (IETF-compliant RFC 2822 timestamps and also a version of ISO8601).

defs.name: from_time
defs.docs:
Creates a JavaScript Date instance that represents a single moment in time.
 Date objects are based on a time value that is the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 UTC.
 
 Integer value representing the number of milliseconds since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC,
 with leap seconds ignored (Unix Epoch; but consider that most Unix timestamp functions count in seconds).

defs.name: utc
defs.value: fn (year: i32, month: i32, day: i32, hours: i32, minutes: i32, seconds: i32, milliseconds: i32) -> f64
defs.docs:
The Date.UTC() method accepts the same parameters as the longest form of the constructor, and
 returns the number of milliseconds in a Date object since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00, universal time.

defs.name: parse
defs.docs:
The Date.parse() method parses a string representation of a date, and returns the number of
 milliseconds since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC or NaN if the string is unrecognized or, in
 some cases, contains illegal date values (e.g. 2015-02-31).

defs.name: now
defs.docs: The Date.now() method returns the number of milliseconds elapsed since 1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC.

defs.name: get_date
defs.docs: The getDate() method returns the day of the month for the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_day
defs.docs:
The getDay() method returns the day of the week for the specified date according to local time,
 where 0 represents Sunday. For the day of the month see getDate().

defs.name: get_full_year
defs.docs: The getFullYear() method returns the year of the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_hours
defs.docs: The getHours() method returns the hour for the specified date, according to local time.

defs.name: get_milliseconds
defs.docs: The getMilliseconds() method returns the milliseconds in the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_minutes
defs.docs: The getMinutes() method returns the minutes in the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_month
defs.docs:
The getMonth() method returns the month in the specified date according to local time, as a
 zero-based value (where zero indicates the first month of the year).

defs.name: get_seconds
defs.docs: The getSeconds() method returns the seconds in the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_time
defs.docs:
The getTime() method returns the numeric value corresponding to the time for the specified
 date according to universal time.

defs.name: get_timezone_offset
defs.docs: The getTimezoneOffset() method returns the time zone difference, in minutes, from current locale (host system settings) to UTC.

defs.name: get_utc_date
defs.docs:
The getUTCDate() method returns the day (date) of the month in the specified date according to
 universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_day
defs.docs:
The getUTCDay() method returns the day of the week in the specified date according to universal
 time, where 0 represents Sunday.

defs.name: get_utc_full_year
defs.docs: The getUTCFullYear() method returns the year in the specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_hours
defs.docs: The getUTCHours() method returns the hours in the specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_milliseconds
defs.docs:
The getUTCMilliseconds() method returns the milliseconds in the specified date according to
 universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_minutes
defs.docs: The getUTCMinutes() method returns the minutes in the specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_month
defs.docs:
The getUTCMonth() returns the month of the specified date according to universal time, as a
 zero-based value (where zero indicates the first month of the year).

defs.name: get_utc_seconds
defs.docs: The getUTCSeconds() method returns the seconds in the specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_date
defs.docs: The setDate() method sets the day of the Date object relative to the beginning of the currently set month.

defs.name: set_full_year
defs.docs: The setFullYear() method sets the full year for a specified date according to local time. Returns new timestamp.

defs.name: set_hours
defs.docs:
The setHours() method sets the hours for a specified date according to local time, and returns the number of milliseconds
 since January 1, 1970 00:00:00 UTC until the time represented by the updated Date instance.

defs.name: set_milliseconds
defs.docs: The setMilliseconds() method sets the milliseconds for a specified date according to local time.

defs.name: set_minutes
defs.docs: The setMinutes() method sets the minutes for a specified date according to local time.

defs.name: set_month
defs.docs: The setMonth() method sets the month for a specified date according to the currently set year.

defs.name: set_seconds
defs.docs: The setSeconds() method sets the seconds for a specified date according to local time.

defs.name: set_time
defs.docs:
The setTime() method sets the Date object to the time represented by a number of milliseconds since
 January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC.

defs.name: set_utc_date
defs.docs: The setUTCDate() method sets the day of the month for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_full_year
defs.docs: The setUTCFullYear() method sets the full year for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_hours
defs.docs:
The setUTCHours() method sets the hour for a specified date according to universal time, and returns the number
 of milliseconds since  January 1, 1970 00:00:00 UTC until the time represented by the updated Date instance.

defs.name: set_utc_milliseconds
defs.docs: The setUTCMilliseconds() method sets the milliseconds for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_minutes
defs.docs: The setUTCMinutes() method sets the minutes for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_month
defs.docs: The setUTCMonth() method sets the month for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_seconds
defs.docs: The setUTCSeconds() method sets the seconds for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: to_date_string
defs.docs: The toDateString() method returns the date portion of a Date object in human readable form in American English.

defs.name: to_iso_string
defs.docs:
The toISOString() method returns a string in simplified extended ISO format (ISO 8601), which is always 24 or 27
 characters long (YYYY-MM-DDTHH:mm:ss.sssZ or YYYYYY-MM-DDTHH:mm:ss.sssZ, respectively). The timezone is always zero
 UTC offset, as denoted by the suffix "Z".

defs.name: to_json
defs.docs: The toJSON() method returns a string representation of the Date object.

defs.name: to_string
defs.docs: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified Date object.

defs.name: to_time_string
defs.docs: The toTimeString() method returns the time portion of a Date object in human readable form in American English.

defs.name: to_utc_string
defs.docs: The toUTCString() method converts a date to a string, using the UTC time zone.

defs.name: value_of
defs.docs: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of a Date object.

defs.name: Document
defs.docs:
The `Document` interface represents any web page loaded in the browser and
 serves as an entry point into the web page's content, which is the DOM tree.

defs.name: document
defs.docs: A global instance of [Document](struct.Document.html).

defs.name: create_document_fragment
defs.docs:
In an HTML document, the Document.createDocumentFragment() method creates a
 new empty DocumentFragment.

defs.name: create_element
defs.docs:
In an HTML document, the Document.createElement() method creates the HTML
 element specified by `tag`, or an HTMLUnknownElement if `tag` isn't
 recognized. In other documents, it creates an element with a null namespace URI.

defs.name: create_element_ns
defs.docs:
Creates an element with the specified namespace URI and qualified name.
 To create an element without specifying a namespace URI, use the `createElement` method.

defs.name: create_text_node
defs.docs: Creates a new text node.

defs.name: location
defs.docs:
Returns a [Location](struct.Location.html) object which contains
 information about the URL of the document and provides methods
 for changing that URL and loading another URL.

defs.name: body
defs.docs: Returns the `<body>` or `<frameset>` node of the current document, or null if no such element exists.

defs.name: head
defs.docs:
Returns the `<head>` element of the current document. If there are more than one `<head>`
 elements, the first one is returned.

defs.name: title
defs.docs: Gets the title of the document.

defs.name: set_title
defs.docs: Sets the title of the document.

defs.name: document_element
defs.docs:
Returns the Element that is the root element of the document (for example, the `<html>`
 element for HTML documents).

defs.name: pointer_lock_element
defs.docs: Returns the Element that the pointer is locked to, if it is locked to any

defs.name: exit_pointer_lock
defs.docs: Exit the pointer lock on the current element

defs.name: import_node
defs.value: fn <N> (&self, n: &N, kind: CloneKind) -> Result<Node, NotSupportedError>
defs.docs: Import node from another document

defs.name: fullscreen_enabled
defs.docs: Check if the fullscreen API is enabled

defs.name: fullscreen_element
defs.docs: Get the current fullscreen element, or None if there is nothing fullscreen

defs.name: RequestAnimationFrameHandle
defs.docs: A handle to a pending animation frame request.

defs.name: cancel
defs.docs: Cancels an animation frame request.

defs.name: Window
defs.docs: The `Window` object represents a window containing a DOM document.

defs.name: window
defs.docs: A global instance of [Window](struct.Window.html).

defs.name: alert
defs.docs:
The Window.alert() method displays an alert dialog
 with the optional specified content and an OK button.

defs.name: confirm
defs.docs:
The Window.confirm() method displays a modal dialog
 with an optional message and two buttons: OK and Cancel.

defs.name: local_storage
defs.docs:
The `local_storage` property allows you to access a local [Storage](struct.Storage.html)
 object.

defs.name: session_storage
defs.docs:
The `session_storage` property allows you to access a session [Storage](struct.Storage.html)
 object for the current origin.

defs.name: location
defs.docs:
Returns a [Location](struct.Location.html) object which contains
 information about the URL of the document and provides methods
 for changing that URL and loading another URL.

defs.name: request_animation_frame
defs.docs:
You should call this method whenever you're ready to update your animation onscreen.
 This will request that your animation function be called before the browser performs the next repaint.
 The number of callbacks is usually 60 times per second, but will generally match the display refresh
 rate in most web browsers as per W3C recommendation. request_animation_frame() calls are paused in most browsers
 when running in background tabs or hidden iframes in order to improve performance and battery life.

defs.name: history
defs.docs:
Returns the global [History](struct.History.html) object, which provides methods to
 manipulate the browser history.

defs.name: inner_width
defs.docs:
Returns the width (in pixels) of the browser window viewport including, if rendered,
 the vertical scrollbar.

defs.name: inner_height
defs.docs:
Returns the height (in pixels) of the browser window viewport including, if rendered,
 the horizontal scrollbar.

defs.name: outer_width
defs.docs:
Returns the width of the outside of the browser window. It represents the width
 of the whole browser window including sidebar (if expanded), window chrome
 and window resizing borders/handles.

defs.name: outer_height
defs.docs:
Returns the height of the outside of the browser window. It represents the height
 of the whole browser window including sidebar (if expanded), window chrome
 and window resizing borders/handles.

defs.name: page_y_offset
defs.docs:
The read-only Window property pageYOffset is an alias for scrollY; as such, it returns
 the number of pixels the document is currently scrolled along the vertical axis (that is,
 up or down), with a value of 0.0 indicating that the top edge of the Document is currently
 aligned with the top edge of the window's content area.

defs.name: page_x_offset
defs.docs: This is an alias for scrollX.

defs.name: device_pixel_ratio
defs.docs: The ratio in resolution from physical pixels to CSS pixels

defs.name: get_selection
defs.docs:
Returns a [Selection](struct.Selection.html) object representing the range of text selected
 by the user or the current position of the caret.
 [(Javascript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/getSelection)

defs.name: IEvent
defs.docs:
The `IEvent` interface represents any event which takes place in the DOM; some
 are user-generated (such as mouse or keyboard events), while others are
 generated by APIs (such as events that indicate an animation has finished
 running, a video has been paused, and so forth). There are many types of event,
 some of which useother interfaces based on the main `IEvent` interface. `IEvent`
 itself contains the properties and methods which are common to all events.

defs.name: bubbles
defs.docs: Indicates whether this event bubbles upward through the DOM.

defs.name: cancel_bubble
defs.docs: A historical alias to `Event.stopPropagation()`.

defs.name: set_cancel_bubble
defs.docs:
A historical alias to `Event.stopPropagation()`.
 Setting this to `true` before returning from an event handler will stop propagation
 of the event.

defs.name: cancelable
defs.docs: Indicates whether the event is cancelable.

defs.name: current_target
defs.docs: A reference to the currently registered target of this event.

defs.name: default_prevented
defs.docs: Indicates whether `preventDefault` has been called on this event.

defs.name: event_phase
defs.docs: Indicates which phase of event flow is currently being evaluated.

defs.name: stop_immediate_propagation
defs.docs: Prevents any further listeners from being called for this event.

defs.name: stop_propagation
defs.docs: Stops the propagation of this event to descendants in the DOM.

defs.name: target
defs.docs: Returns a reference to the target to which this event was originally registered.

defs.name: time_stamp
defs.docs: Returns the time in milliseconds at which this event was created.

defs.name: is_trusted
defs.docs: Indicates whether the event was generated by a user action.

defs.name: event_type
defs.docs:
Returnsa string containing the type of event. It is set when
 the event is constructed and is the name commonly used to refer
 to the specific event.

defs.name: prevent_default
defs.docs:
Cancels the event if it is cancelable, without
 stopping further propagation of the event.

defs.name: None
defs.docs: No event is currently being processed.

defs.name: Capturing
defs.docs: The event is being propagated down through the target's ancestors.

defs.name: AtTarget
defs.docs: The target is currently processing the event.

defs.name: Bubbling
defs.docs: The event is propagating back up through the target's ancestors.

defs.name: EventPhase
defs.docs: Indicates the phase of event flow during event proessing.

defs.name: ConcreteEvent
defs.docs: A trait representing a concrete event type.

defs.name: EVENT_TYPE
defs.docs: A string representing the event type.

defs.name: Event
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IEvent](trait.IEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: BeforeUnloadEvent
defs.docs:
The `BeforeUnload` event fires when the window is about to be unloaded (to close the page or
 follow a link). If the event propagation is cancelled, the browser will present the user with
 a confirmation dialog allowing them to stay on the page or continue.

defs.name: UnloadEvent
defs.docs:
The `Unload` event fires when the window has been unloaded and is no longer visible. This event
 can't be cancelled.

defs.name: FullscreenChangeEvent
defs.docs: The 'FullscreenChange' event fires when an element enters or exits fullscreen

defs.name: IUiEvent
defs.docs: The `IUiEvent` interface represents simple user interface events.

defs.name: detail
defs.docs: Provides the current click count for this event, if applicable.

defs.name: view
defs.docs: Returns the `WindowProxy` that generated the event.

defs.name: UiEvent
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IUiEvent](trait.IUiEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: EventListenerHandle
defs.docs: A handle to a particular event listener.

defs.name: remove
defs.docs:
Removes the listener from the [IEventTarget](trait.IEventTarget.html) on
 which it was previously registered.

defs.name: IEventTarget
defs.docs:
`IEventTarget` is an interface implemented by objects that
 can receive events and may have listeners for them.

defs.name: add_event_listener
defs.docs:
Adds given event handler to the list of event listeners for
 the specified `EventTarget` on which it's called.

defs.name: dispatch_event
defs.docs:
Dispatches an `Event` at this `EventTarget`, invoking the affected event listeners in the
 appropriate order.

defs.name: EventTarget
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IEventTarget](trait.IEventTarget.html)
 interface.

defs.name: Shallow
defs.docs: Will not clone the children.

defs.name: Deep
defs.docs: Will clone the children.

defs.name: CloneKind
defs.docs: An enum which determines whenever the DOM [Node](trait.INode.html)'s children will also be cloned or not.

defs.name: INode
defs.docs: `INode` is an interface from which a number of DOM API object types inherit.

defs.name: as_node
defs.docs: Casts a reference to this object into a reference to a [Node](struct.Node.html).

defs.name: append_child
defs.docs: Adds a node to the end of the list of children of a specified parent node.

defs.name: remove_child
defs.docs: Removes a child node from the DOM.

defs.name: clone_node
defs.docs: Returns a duplicate of the node on which this method was called.

defs.name: contains
defs.docs: Checks whenever a given node is a descendant of this one or not.

defs.name: insert_before
defs.value: fn <T, U> (&self, new_node: &T, reference_node: &U) -> Result<Node, InsertNodeError>
defs.docs: Inserts the specified node before the reference node as a child of the current node.

defs.name: IElement
defs.docs:
The `IElement` interface represents an object of a [Document](struct.Document.html).
 This interface describes methods and properties common to all
 kinds of elements.

defs.name: namespace_uri
defs.docs:
The Element.namespaceURI read-only property returns the namespace URI
 of the element, or null if the element is not in a namespace.

defs.name: class_list
defs.docs:
The Element.classList is a read-only property which returns alive
 [TokenList](struct.TokenList.html) collection of the class attributes
 of the element.

defs.name: has_attribute
defs.docs:
The Element.hasAttribute() method returns a Boolean value indicating whether
 the specified element has the specified attribute or not.

defs.name: get_attribute
set_attribute
defs.docs:
Sets the value of an attribute on the specified element. If the attribute already
 exists, the value is updated; otherwise a new attribute is added with the
 specified name and value.

defs.name: scroll_top
defs.docs: Gets the the number of pixels that an element's content is scrolled vertically.

defs.name: set_scroll_top
defs.docs: Sets the the number of pixels that an element's content is scrolled vertically.

defs.name: scroll_left
defs.docs: Gets the the number of pixels that an element's content is scrolled to the left.

defs.name: set_scroll_left
defs.docs: Sets the the number of pixels that an element's content is scrolled to the left.

defs.name: get_attribute_names
defs.docs:
Element.getAttributeNames() returns the attribute names of the element
 as an Array of strings. If the element has no attributes it returns an empty array.

defs.name: remove_attribute
defs.docs: Element.removeAttribute removes an attribute from the specified element.

defs.name: has_attributes
defs.docs:
The Element.hasAttributes() method returns Boolean value, indicating if
 the current element has any attributes or not.

defs.name: closest
defs.docs:
Returns the closest ancestor of the element (or the element itself) which matches the selectors 
 given in parameter. If there isn't such an ancestor, it returns
 `None`.

defs.name: set_pointer_capture
defs.docs: Designates a specific element as the capture target of future pointer events.

defs.name: release_pointer_capture
defs.docs: Releases pointer capture that was previously set for a specific pointer

defs.name: has_pointer_capture
defs.docs: Returns a boolean indicating if the element has captured the specified pointer

defs.name: insert_html_after

defs.name: slot
defs.docs:
The slot property of the Element interface returns the name of the shadow DOM

defs.name: attach_shadow

Attach a shadow DOM tree to the specified element and returns a reference to its `ShadowRoot`.
 It returns a shadow root if successfully attached or `None` if the element cannot be attached.

defs.name: shadow_root
defs.docs: Returns the shadow root of the current element or `None`.

defs.name: Element

A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IElement](trait.IElement.html)

defs.name: AfterBegin
defs.docs: Insert at the start of the reference element.

defs.name: BeforeEnd
defs.docs: Insert at the end of the reference element.

defs.name: AfterEnd
defs.docs: Insert into the parent directly after the reference element.

defs.name: Rect
defs.docs:
Represents a rectangle.
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRect)

defs.name: get_x
defs.docs:
Represents the x coordinate of the DOMRect's origin
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRectReadOnly/x)

defs.name: get_y
defs.docs:
Represents the y coordinate of the DOMRect's origin.
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRectReadOnly/y)

defs.name: get_width
defs.docs:
Represents the width of the DOMRect.
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRectReadOnly/width)

defs.name: get_height
defs.docs:
Represents the height of the DOMRect.
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRectReadOnly/height)

defs.name: get_top
defs.docs:
Returns the top coordinate value of the DOMRect. (Has the same value as y, or y + height if height is negative.)
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRectReadOnly/top)

defs.name: get_right
defs.docs:
Returns the right coordinate value of the DOMRect. (Has the same value as x + width, or x if width is negative.)
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRectReadOnly/right)

defs.name: get_bottom
defs.docs:
Returns the bottom coordinate value of the DOMRect. (Has the same value as y + height, or y if height is negative.)
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRectReadOnly/bottom)

defs.name: get_left
defs.docs:
Returns the left coordinate value of the DOMRect. (Has the same value as x, or x + width if width is negative.)
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/DOMRectReadOnly/left)

defs.name: IHtmlElement
defs.docs: The `IHtmlElement` interface represents any HTML element.

defs.name: focus
defs.docs: Sets focus on the specified element, if it can be focused.

defs.name: blur
defs.docs: Removes keyboard focus from the current element.

defs.name: dataset
defs.docs:
Allows access, both in reading and writing, to all of the custom data attributes (data-*)
 set on the element, either in HTML or in the DOM.

defs.name: get_bounding_client_rect
defs.docs:
Returns the size of an element and its position relative to the viewport.
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Element/getBoundingClientRect)

defs.name: offset_width
defs.docs:
Returns the layout width of an element. Typically, an element's offsetWidth is a
 measurement which includes the element borders, the element horizontal padding, the
 element vertical scrollbar (if present, if rendered) and the element CSS width.

defs.name: offset_height
defs.docs:
Returns the height of the element including vertical padding and borders, as an
 integer.

defs.name: inner_text
defs.docs:
A property which represents the "rendered" text content of a node and its descendants.
 It approximates the text the user would get if they highlighted the contents of the element
 with the cursor and then copied to the clipboard.

defs.name: HtmlElement
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IHtmlElement](trait.IHtmlElement.html)
 interface.

defs.name: CanvasElement
defs.docs:
The HTML `<canvas>` element provides an empty graphic zone on which specific JavaScript APIs
 can draw (such as Canvas 2D or WebGL).

defs.name: height
defs.docs:
Returns a positive integer reflecting the height HTML attribute of the <canvas> element
 interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an
 invalid value, like a negative, the default value of 150 is used.

defs.name: set_height
defs.docs:
Sets a positive integer reflecting the height HTML attribute of the <canvas> element
 interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an
 invalid value, like a negative, the default value of 150 is used.

defs.name: width
defs.docs:
Returns a positive integer reflecting the width HTML attribute of the <canvas> element
 interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an
 invalid value, like a negative, the default value of 300 is used.

defs.name: set_width
defs.docs:
Sets a positive integer reflecting the width HTML attribute of the <canvas> element
 interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an
 invalid value, like a negative, the default value of 300 is used.

defs.name: get_context
defs.docs: Returns a drawing context on the canvas, or None if the context identifier is not supported.

defs.name: to_data_url
defs.value: fn (&self, mime_type: Option<&str>, quality: Option<f64>) -> Result<String, TODO>
defs.docs:
Returns a data URI containing a representation of the image in the format specified by the
 type parameter (defaults to PNG). The returned image is in a resolution of 96 dpi.

defs.name: to_blob
defs.value: fn <F> (&self, f: F, mime_type: Option<&str>, quality: Option<f64>) -> Result<(), TODO>
defs.docs:
Creates a Blob object representing the image contained in the canvas; this file may be
 cached on the disk or stored in memory at the discretion of the user agent.

defs.docs: Sets the HTML `alt` attribute, representing the fallback context for the image.

defs.name: complete
defs.docs:
Returns true if the browser has finished fetching the image, whether
 successful or not. It also return true if the image has no src value.

defs.name: cross_origin
defs.docs: Returns the Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) setting for the image.

defs.name: set_cross_origin
defs.docs: Sets the Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) setting for the image.

defs.name: height
defs.docs: Returns the the rendered height of the image in CSS pixels.

defs.name: set_height
defs.docs: Sets the the rendered height of the image in CSS pixels.

defs.name: is_map

defs.name: set_is_map
defs.docs: Sets whether the image is part of a server-side image map.

defs.name: natural_height
defs.docs: Returns the intrinsic height of the image in CSS pixels, if it is available.

defs.name: natural_width
defs.docs: Returns the intrinsic width of the image in CSS pixels, if it is available.

defs.name: src
defs.docs: Returns the full URL of the image, including the base URI.

defs.name: set_src
defs.docs: Sets the full URL of the image, including the base URI.

defs.name: use_map

defs.name: set_use_map
defs.docs: Sets the `usemap` HTML attribute, containing a partial URL of a map element.

defs.name: width
defs.docs: Returns the rendered width of the image in CSS pixels.

defs.name: set_width
defs.docs: Sets the rendered width of the image in CSS pixels.

defs.name: InputElement
defs.docs:
The HTML input element is used to create interactive controls
 for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user.

defs.name: raw_value
defs.docs: The value of the control. This attribute is optional except when the input is a radio button or a checkbox.

defs.name: set_raw_value
defs.docs: Sets the value of the control.

defs.name: selection_start
defs.docs:
The offset to the start of the selection.
 This attribute only applies when the input is a text, search, url, telephone or password.

defs.name: set_selection_start
defs.docs:
Sets the offset to the start of the selection.
 This attribute only applies when the input is a text, search, url, telephone or password.

defs.name: selection_end
defs.docs:
The offset to the end of the selection.
 This attribute only applies when the input is a text, search, url, telephone or password.

defs.name: set_selection_end
defs.docs:
Sets the offset to the end of the selection.
 This attribute only applies when the input is a text, search, url, telephone or password.

defs.name: TextAreaElement
defs.docs: The HTML `<textarea>` element represents a multi-line plain-text editing control.

defs.name: value
defs.docs: The value of the control.

defs.name: set_value
defs.docs: Sets the value of the control.

defs.name: UnknownValueError
defs.docs:
Indicates that an invalid value is setted to an `SelectElement`.
 It means there is no `<option>` element that has the given value.

defs.name: SelectElement
defs.docs: The HTML `<select>` element represents a control that provides a menu of options.

defs.name: raw_value
defs.docs:
Returns the value attribute of the first selected `<option>` element or
 if it is missing, the text attribute. If there is no selection, return empty string.
 This method is just a wrapper for getting `HTMLSelectElement.value` directly

defs.name: set_raw_value
defs.docs: Set the given value to `HTMLSelectElement.value` directly.

defs.name: selected_index
defs.docs: Returns the `Some(index)` of the first selected item, if any, or `None` if there is no selected item.

defs.name: set_selected_index
defs.docs: Change selected index to the given value.

defs.name: value
defs.docs: Returns the `Some(value)` of the first selected item, if any, or `None` if there is no selected item.

defs.name: set_value
defs.docs:
Change the selected value to the given value. If you provide an invalid value,
 the `<select>` element will have no item selected, and an `UnknownValueError` is returned.

defs.name: multiple
defs.docs: Indicates whether multiple items can be selected

defs.name: selected_options
defs.docs:
An `HtmlCollection` representing
 the set of `<option>` elements that are selected.

defs.name: selected_values
defs.docs: A convenience method to get values of all selected `<option>` elements

defs.name: selected_indices
defs.docs: A convenience method to get indices of all selected `<option>` elements

defs.name: OptionElement
defs.docs:
The HTML `<option>` element is used to define an item contained in a `<select>`,
 an `<optgroup>`, or a `<datalist>` element.

defs.name: index
defs.docs:
The position of the option within the list of options it belongs to, in tree-order.
 If the option is not part of a list of options, like when it is part of
 the `<datalist>` element, the value is 0.

defs.name: value
defs.docs:
Reflects the value of the value HTML attribute, if it exists;
 otherwise reflects value of the `Node.textContent` property.

defs.name: TemplateElement
defs.docs:
The HTML `<template>` element represents a mechanism for holding client-side content
 that is not to be rendered when a page is loaded but may subsequently be instantiated
 during runtime using JavaScript.

defs.name: content
defs.docs: The content of the current template

defs.name: AssignedOnly
defs.docs: Will only return content assigned.

defs.name: WithFallback
defs.docs: Will return the fallback content if nothing has been assigned.

defs.name: SlotContentKind
defs.docs:
An enum which determines whether
 [SlotElement::assigned_nodes](struct.SlotElement.html#method.assigned_nodes) /
 [SlotElement::assigned_elements](struct.SlotElement.html#method.assigned_elements) will
 return the fallback content when nothing has been assigned to the slot.

defs.name: SlotElement
defs.docs:
The HTML `<slot>` element represents a placeholder inside a web component that

 present them together.

defs.name: name
defs.docs: The slot's name

defs.name: set_name
defs.docs: Setter of name.

defs.name: assigned_nodes
defs.docs: Returns slot's assigned nodes.

defs.name: assigned_elements
defs.docs: Similar to [assigned_nodes()](#method.assigned_nodes) but limited result to only elements.

defs.name: IWindowOrWorker
defs.docs:
The `IWindowOrWorker` mixin describes several features common to
 the `Window` and the global scope of web workers.

defs.name: TokenList

defs.name: len

defs.name: item
defs.docs: Returns a node from a NodeList by index.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs: Returns an iterator over the list.

defs.name: StringMap

defs.name: insert

defs.docs: Removes a key from the map.

defs.name: contains_key

defs.docs:
The `Location` interface represents the location (URL) of the object it
 is linked to. Changes done on it are reflected on the object it relates
 to. Both the [Document](struct.Document.html) and [Window](struct.Window.html)
 interface have such a linked `Location`, accessible via [Document::location](struct.Document.html#method.location)
 and [Window::location](struct.Window.html#method.location) respectively.

defs.name: href
defs.docs: The entire URL.

defs.name: origin
defs.docs:
Returns a `String` containing the Unicode serialization of the origin of the represented
 URL, that is:

defs.name: protocol
defs.docs: Returns a `String` representing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final ':'.

defs.name: host
defs.docs:
Returns a `String` containing the host (i.e. hostname) and then, if the port of the
 URL is nonempty, a ':', and the port of the URL.

defs.name: hostname
defs.docs: Returns a `String` which is the domain of the URL

defs.name: port
defs.docs: Returns a `String` containing the port number or `""` if there is no port.

defs.name: pathname
defs.docs: Returns a `String` containing an initial '/' followed by the path of the URL.

defs.docs:

Returns a `String` containing a '#' followed by the fragment

defs.name: get
defs.docs: Returns a value corresponding to the key.

defs.docs: Inserts a key-value pair into the storage.

defs.name: remove

defs.docs: When invoked, will empty all keys out of the storage.

defs.name: key
defs.docs: Return the name of the nth key in the storage.

defs.name: contains_key
defs.docs: Returns true if the storage contains a value for the specified key.

 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Blob/slice)

defs.name: slice_with_content_type

defs.name: FileList
len

defs.name: iter

defs.name: FileReader
defs.docs:
The FileReader object lets web applications asynchronously read the contents of files
 (or raw data buffers) stored on the user's computer, using [File](struct.File.html)

defs.name: String
defs.docs: A string; a result of calling [FileReader::read_as_text](struct.FileReader.html#method.read_as_text).

defs.name: FileReaderResult
defs.docs: The [result](struct.FileReader.html#method.result) of a read operation performed with a [FileReader](struct.File.html).

defs.docs: No data has been loaded yet.

defs.name: Loading
defs.docs: Data is currently being loaded.

The file's contents. This method will only return a value after the read operation
 is complete, and the format of the data depends on which of the methods was used
 to initiate the read operation.

defs.name: ArrayBuffer

The `ArrayBuffer` object is used to represent a generic, fixed-length raw binary data buffer.
 You cannot directly manipulate the contents of an ArrayBuffer; instead, you create an [TypedArray](struct.TypedArray.html)

defs.name: len

defs.name: to_vec

defs.name: XmlHttpRequest
defs.docs:
Use XmlHttpRequest (XHR) objects to interact with servers.
 You can retrieve data from a URL without having to do a full page refresh.
 This enables a Web page to update just part of a page without disrupting
 what the user is doing. XmlHttpRequest is used heavily in Ajax programming.

defs.name: Unsent
defs.docs: Client has been created. [open()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.open) not called yet.

defs.name: Opened
defs.docs: [open()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.open) has been called.

defs.name: HeadersReceived
defs.docs: [send()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.send) has been called, and headers and [status()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.status) are available.

defs.name: Loading
defs.docs: Downloading; [reponse_text()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.reponse_text) holds partial data.

defs.name: Done
defs.docs: The operation is complete.

defs.name: XhrReadyState

defs.name: Blob

defs.name: Document

defs.name: Json

defs.name: Text

defs.name: XhrResponseType

defs.name: XhrSetResponseTypeError

defs.name: new

defs.name: ready_state

defs.name: response_type

defs.name: set_response_type
defs.docs: Set the type that the XmlHttpRequest should return

defs.name: response_text
defs.docs:
Returns a string that contains the response to the request as text, or None
 if the request was unsuccessful or has not yet been sent.

defs.name: raw_response
defs.docs: Returns the object representing the response

defs.name: status
defs.docs: Returns an unsigned short with the status of the response of the request.

defs.name: open
defs.docs: Open connection with given method (ie GET or POST), and the url to hit.

defs.name: get_response_header
defs.docs:
Returns the string containing the text of the specified header. If there
 are multiple response headers with the same name, then their values are
 returned as a single concatenated string.

defs.name: set_request_header
defs.docs:
Sets the value of an HTTP request header. Must be called after `open()`,
 but before `send()`. If this method is called several times with the same
 header, the values are merged into one single request header.

defs.name: send
defs.docs: Send request on an open connection with no data

defs.name: send_with_string
defs.docs: Send request on an open connection with string body

defs.name: send_with_bytes
defs.docs: Send request on an open connection with a byte array body

defs.name: abort
defs.docs:
Aborts the request if it has already been sent.
 When a request is aborted, its [ready_state](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.ready_state) is changed to [Done](enum.XhrReadyState.html#variant.Done)
 and the [status](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.status) code is set to
 [Unsent](enum.XhrReadyState.html#variant.Unsent).

defs.name: History
defs.docs: [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/History)

defs.name: push_state
defs.value: fn <T> (&self, state: T, title: &str, url: Option<&str>) -> ()
defs.docs: Adds a new entry to history.

defs.name: replace_state
defs.value: fn <T> (&self, state: T, title: &str, url: Option<&str>) -> Result<(), TODO>
defs.docs:
Operates exactly like history.push_state() except that replace_state() modifies the current
 history entry instead of creating a new one. Note that this doesn't prevent the creation of
 a new entry in the global browser history.

defs.name: go
defs.docs:
You can use the go() method to load a specific page from session history, identified by its
 relative position to the current page (with the current page being, of course, relative
 index 0).

defs.name: back
defs.docs: Move one step backward through history.

defs.name: forward
defs.docs: Move one step forward through history.

defs.name: len
defs.docs: Returns the current number of history entries.

defs.name: SocketCloseCode
defs.docs: Wrapper type around a CloseEvent code, indicating why the WebSocket was closed

defs.name: NORMAL_CLOSURE
defs.docs:
Normal closure; the connection successfully completed whatever purpose for which it was
 created.

defs.name: GOING_AWAY
defs.docs:
The endpoint is going away, either because of a server failure or because the browser is
 navigating away from the page that opened the connection.

defs.name: PROTOCOL_ERROR
defs.docs: The endpoint is terminating the connection due to a protocol error.

defs.name: UNSUPPORTED_DATA
defs.docs:
The connection is being terminated because the endpoint received data of a type it cannot
 accept (for example, a text-only endpoint received binary data).

defs.name: NO_STATUS_RECEIVED
defs.docs: Reserved. Indicates that no status code was provided even though one was expected.

defs.name: ABNORMAL_CLOSURE
defs.docs:
Reserved. Used to indicate that a connection was closed abnormally (that is, with no close
 frame being sent) when a status code is expected.

defs.name: INVALID_FRAME_PAYLOAD_DATA
defs.docs:
The endpoint is terminating the connection because a message was received that contained
 inconsistent data (e.g., non-UTF-8 data within a text message).

defs.name: POLICY_VIOLATION
defs.docs:
The endpoint is terminating the connection because it received a message that violates its
 policy. This is a generic status code, used when codes 1003 and 1009 are not suitable.

defs.name: MESSAGE_TOO_BIG
defs.docs:
The endpoint is terminating the connection because a data frame was received that is too
 large.

defs.name: MISSING_EXTENSION
defs.docs:
The client is terminating the connection because it expected the server to negotiate one or
 more extensions, but the server didn't.

defs.name: INTERNAL_ERROR
defs.docs:
The server is terminating the connection because it encountered an unexpected condition
 that prevented it from fulfilling the request.

defs.name: SERVICE_RESTART
defs.docs: The server is terminating the connection because it is restarting.

defs.name: TRY_AGAIN_LATER
defs.docs:
The server is terminating the connection due to a temporary condition, e.g. it is
 overloaded and is casting off some of its clients.

defs.name: BAD_GATEWAY
defs.docs:
The server was acting as a gateway or proxy and received an invalid response from the
 upstream server. This is similar to 502 HTTP Status Code.

defs.name: TLS_HANDSHAKE
defs.docs:
Reserved. Indicates that the connection was closed due to a failure to perform a TLS
 handshake (e.g., the server certificate can't be verified).

defs.name: WebSocket
defs.docs:
The WebSocket object provides the API for creating and managing a WebSocket connection to a
 server, as well as for sending and receiving data on the connection.

defs.name: Blob
defs.docs:
A Blob object represents a file-like object of immutable, raw data.
 [(Javascript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Blob)

defs.name: ArrayBuffer
defs.docs:
The ArrayBuffer object is used to represent a generic, fixed-length raw binary data buffer.
 [(Javascript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/ArrayBuffer)

defs.name: SocketBinaryType
defs.docs: The type of binary data being transmitted by the WebSocket connection.

defs.name: SocketReadyState
defs.docs: A number indicating the state of the `WebSocket`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Returns a newly constructed `WebSocket`.

defs.name: new_with_protocols
defs.docs: Returns a newly constructed `WebSocket`.

defs.name: binary_type
defs.docs:
Returns the binary type of the web socket. Only affects received messages.
 The default binary type is `Blob`.

defs.name: set_binary_type
defs.docs:
Sets the binary type of the web socket. Only affects received messages.
 The default binary type is `Blob`.

defs.name: buffered_amount
defs.docs:
Returns the number of bytes of data that have been queued using calls to send()
 but not yet transmitted to the network. This value resets to zero once all queued
 data has been sent. This value does not reset to zero when the connection is closed;
 if you keep calling send(), this will continue to climb.

defs.name: extensions
defs.docs:
Returns the extensions selected by the server. This is currently only the empty
 string or a list of extensions as negotiated by the connection.

defs.name: protocol
ready_state
defs.docs: Returns the current state of the connection.

defs.name: url
defs.docs: Returns the URL as resolved by the constructor. This is always an absolute URL.

defs.name: close
defs.docs:
Closes the WebSocket connection or connection attempt, if any. If the connection
 is already CLOSED, this method does nothing.

defs.name: close_with_status
defs.value: fn (&self, code: SocketCloseCode, reason: &str) -> Result<(), CloseError>
defs.docs:
Closes the WebSocket connection or connection attempt, if any. If the connection
 is already CLOSED, this method does nothing.

defs.name: send_text
defs.docs:
Enqueues the specified data to be transmitted to the server over the WebSocket
 connection, increasing the value of bufferedAmount by the number of bytes needed
 to contain the data. If the data can't be sent (for example, because it needs to
 be buffered but the buffer is full), the socket is closed automatically.

defs.name: send_blob
defs.docs:
Enqueues the specified data to be transmitted to the server over the WebSocket
 connection, increasing the value of bufferedAmount by the number of bytes needed
 to contain the data. If the data can't be sent (for example, because it needs to
 be buffered but the buffer is full), the socket is closed automatically.

defs.name: send_array_buffer
defs.docs:
Enqueues the specified data to be transmitted to the server over the WebSocket
 connection, increasing the value of bufferedAmount by the number of bytes needed
 to contain the data. If the data can't be sent (for example, because it needs to
 be buffered but the buffer is full), the socket is closed automatically.

defs.name: send_bytes
defs.docs:
Enqueues the specified data to be transmitted to the server over the WebSocket
 connection, increasing the value of bufferedAmount by the number of bytes needed
 to contain the data. If the data can't be sent (for example, because it needs to
 be buffered but the buffer is full), the socket is closed automatically.

defs.name: RenderingContext
defs.docs: Trait implemented by rendering contexts which can be obtained from a canvas.

defs.name: Error
defs.docs: Type of error which can occur whilst creating this context

defs.name: from_canvas
defs.docs: Name which identifies this kind of rendering context.

defs.name: CanvasRenderingContext2d
defs.docs: Used for drawing rectangles, text, images and other objects onto the canvas element.

defs.name: CanvasGradient
defs.docs:
The CanvasGradient struct represents an opaque object describing a gradient.
 It is returned by the methods CanvasRenderingContext2D.createLinearGradient() or
 CanvasRenderingContext2D.createRadialGradient().

defs.name: CanvasPattern
defs.docs:
The CanvasPattern struct represents an opaque object describing a pattern, based on an image,
 a canvas or a video, created by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.createPattern() method.
 Intentionally blank, no non-experimental properties or methods.

defs.name: ImageData
defs.docs:
The ImageData struct represents the underlying pixel data of an area of a `<canvas>` element.
 You can create a new instance by calling [`CanvasRenderingContext2d::create_image_data`](struct.CanvasRenderingContext2d.html#method.create_image_data)
 or [`CanvasRenderingContext2d::create_image_data_size_of`](struct.CanvasRenderingContext2d.html#method.create_image_data_size_of).

defs.name: TextMetrics
defs.docs: The TextMetrics struct represents the dimension of a text in the canvas, as created by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.measureText() method.

defs.name: SourceOver
defs.docs: Draws new shapes over existing canvas content

defs.name: SourceIn
defs.docs: Draws new shapes over existing canvas content, but only where existing canvas content overlaps. Anything not in that area becomes transparent.

defs.name: SourceOut
defs.docs: New shapes are drawn where there is no existing canvas content. Everything else (including old canvas content) is made transparent.

defs.name: SourceAtop
defs.docs: Draws new shapes only where there is existing canvas content, over existing canvas content

defs.name: DestinationOver
defs.docs: Draws new shapes behind existing canvas content

defs.name: DestinationIn
defs.docs: Keeps existing canvas content where it overlaps with the new shape. Everything outside the overlap is made transparent.

defs.name: DestinationOut
defs.docs: The existing content is kept where it doesn't overlap with the new shape. Everything else, including the new shape area, is made transparent.

defs.name: DestinationAtop
defs.docs: Existing content is kept only where it overlaps with the new shape. The new shape is drawn behind the existing content.

defs.name: Lighter
defs.docs: Where both shapes overlap, the new color is determined by adding color values

defs.name: Copy
defs.docs: Only the new shape is shown

defs.name: Xor
defs.docs: Where both shapes overlap, make it transparent

defs.name: Multiply
defs.docs: The pixels of the new and old layer are multiplied. (Pixel values are in the range of [0,1], so this makes a darker picture)

defs.name: Screen
defs.docs: Pixels from both new and old are inverted, multiplied together, then inverted again. (Pixel values are in the range of [0,1], so this makes a lighter picture)

defs.name: Overlay
defs.docs: Applies Multiply to dark colors in the existing content, and Screen to bright colors in the existing content

defs.name: Darken
defs.docs: Retains the darkest pixels

defs.name: Lighten
defs.docs: Retains the lighest pixels

defs.name: ColorDodge
defs.docs: Divides the bottom layer by the inverted top layer.

defs.name: ColorBurn
defs.docs: Divides the inverted bottom layer by the top layer, and then inverts the result.

defs.name: HardLight
defs.docs: A combination of multiply and screen like overlay, but with top and bottom layer swapped.

defs.name: SoftLight
defs.docs: A softer version of hard-light. Pure black or white does not result in pure black or white.

defs.name: Difference
defs.docs: Subtracts the bottom layer from the top layer or the other way round to always get a positive value.

defs.name: Exclusion
defs.docs: Like difference, but with lower contrast.

defs.name: Hue
defs.docs: Preserves the luma and chroma of the bottom layer, while adopting the hue of the top layer.

defs.name: Saturation
defs.docs: Preserves the luma and hue of the bottom layer, while adopting the chroma of the top layer.

defs.name: Color
defs.docs: Preserves the luma of the bottom layer, while adopting the hue and chroma of the top layer.

defs.name: Luminosity
defs.docs: Preserves the hue and chroma of the bottom layer, while adopting the luma of the top layer.

defs.name: LineCap

defs.name: Bevel

defs.name: Round

defs.name: Miter

determines how two connecting segments (of lines, arcs or curves) with non-zero lengths in a shape are

defs.name: RepeatY

defs.name: NoRepeat

defs.name: add_color_stop
defs.value: fn (&self, offset: f64, color: &str) -> Result<(), AddColorStopError>
